docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:1:# How Rhei Is Used
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:7:## Roles
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:11:### Plan Writer
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:24:### Plan Worker
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:26:The plan worker picks up an existing plan and makes progress on it. It is driven entirely by the plan: the state machine defines what transitions are legal, `**Prior:**` edges define what is ready, and state instructions define what to do.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:31:- In interactive/manual execution, advance the state when exit conditions are met (e.g., `draft` → `pending`, `pending` → `agent-review`) or finish directly with `rhei complete` when review is not required.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:32:- In `rhei run` execution, leave state mutation to the orchestrator: the worker produces the required artifacts and exits, and `rhei run` performs the transition.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:35:The plan worker does **not** add tasks, reorder tasks, change dependencies, or delete sections. In interactive/manual execution it may edit `**State:**` values and progress logs inside a task body (including child task bodies). Under `rhei run`, spawned workers leave `**State:**` changes to the orchestrator and only produce the work and artifacts for the current state.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:37:The Plan Worker role corresponds to `worker` [Completion Authority](rhei-agents.spec.md#completion-authority); `rhei run` corresponds to `orchestrator` authority. The same state definition is legal under both — what differs is who decides the state's work is done and drives the resulting transition.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:39:### Reviewer
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:43:- **Agent reviewer** (`agent-review`): An automated pass that checks the implementation against the task description, its child task nodes, and repository conventions (lint, format, tests). It records concrete findings in the task body or in a required findings artifact when the active state machine declares one. The next transition is then chosen by the active execution model: manually by an interactive worker, or by `rhei run` after the reviewer subprocess exits.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:45:- **Human reviewer** (`human-review`): A human inspects the work. No agent may transition out of this state autonomously. The human decides: return to `pending` (rework), `completed` (approve), or `cancelled` (abandon).
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:47:### Human Operator
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:58:## Coordination Through the State Machine
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:66:This means agents do not need to communicate with each other directly. They communicate through artifacts and the authoritative plan state managed by the orchestrator: one agent writes outputs for its state, `rhei run` advances the task, and the next agent reads the resulting state and artifacts.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:68:### State Flow (Default Machine)
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:71:draft --> pending --> agent-review --> completed
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:75:            |        agent-review-fix ----+
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:87:The `human-review` state is deliberately isolated: agents can send work into it (from `pending` or `agent-review`), but only a human can transition out of it. This separation ensures that human judgment gates are never bypassed by automated workflows.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:89:Each arrow is a declared transition. Agents follow the `instructions` field on each state to know what work must be completed before the next handoff. The transition itself is then performed either by an interactive/manual worker or by the `rhei run` orchestrator.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:91:### Command Surface
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:97:| `rhei run`         | Drives the full plan forward under orchestrator authority                       |
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:98:| `rhei next`        | Claims the next ready task for a manual worker (with `--peek` for read-only)    |
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:103:`rhei run` and the manual-worker flow (`next` / `transition` / `complete`) are mutually exclusive per execution — they never overlap on the same task because `rhei run` holds transition responsibility for the states it drives. The typical manual-worker loop is `next` (claim) → work → `transition` (advance as needed) → `complete` (finish, record result, release).
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:105:## Usage Patterns
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:107:### Pattern 0: Zero-Config Agent Execution
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:111:1. Configure your default agent once:
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:115:   echo '{"agent": "claude-code"}' > ~/.config/rhei/settings.json
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:123:   rhei run plan.rhei.md
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:126:Rhei spawns the configured agent for each task, composing a prompt from the state machine instructions and the task content. The agent does the work for the current state, writes any required artifacts, and exits. `rhei run` then performs the state transition. No scaffolding required.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:128:For state-specific agents (e.g., a different agent or model for review):
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:131:# states.yaml
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:135:    agent: claude-code
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:138:  agent-review:
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:140:    agent: codex
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:145:Agents are referenced by string id only — `agent:` is resolved against the
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:146:merged `agents` registry (built-ins + `~/.config/rhei/settings.json` +
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:147:`<plan-root>/.rhei/settings.json`). To use a CLI that isn't a built-in, add
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:148:it to the registry instead of inlining it on the state. Run-time overrides
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:149:are available via `--agent <AGENT>`, `--agent-mode <MODE>`, and `--model
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:150:<MODEL>` on `rhei run`.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:152:For parallel execution of independent tasks:
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:155:rhei run plan.rhei.md --parallel 4
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:158:See [Agents Specification](rhei-agents.spec.md) for configuration, resolution order, timeout handling, and log capture.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:160:### Pattern 1: Single Agent, Start to Finish
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:162:One agent session acts as both writer and worker. This is useful when the agent session itself drives the workflow rather than `rhei run`.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:170:This is the default for small, well-scoped work within a single agent session. The plan still provides value: it gives the human a structured view of progress, and the agent a memory of what it has and hasn't done. For larger work or multi-agent workflows, Pattern 0 (`rhei run`) is preferred.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:172:### Pattern 2: Writer and Worker as Separate Sessions
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:174:For larger work, the plan writer and plan worker run in separate agent sessions — possibly days apart.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:178:3. **Session 2 (execution):** A new agent session invokes the plan worker. It reads the plan fresh, selects the first eligible task, and begins work.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:183:### Pattern 3: Parallel Workers on Independent Branches
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:185:When a plan's DAG has independent branches (tasks with no shared dependencies), multiple workers can operate in parallel.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:188:### Task 1: Set up database schema
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:191:### Task 2: Build API endpoints
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:195:### Task 3: Write frontend components
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:198:### Task 4: Integration tests
