docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:261:### Pattern 5: Draft Expansion
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:263:For exploratory or long-running projects, tasks start as `draft` — placeholder titles that are not yet ready for execution.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:267:3. The agent works in `draft`: it analyzes the current state of the project, determines the most elegant approach, and writes a concrete task description.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:268:4. In interactive/manual execution, the agent transitions `draft` → `pending` via `rhei transition`. Under `rhei run`, the spawned agent exits after writing the concrete task description and any required draft artifacts, and `rhei run` performs the `draft` → `pending` transition.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:269:5. Work then continues in `pending`, either in the same manual session or through the next `rhei run` pass.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:271:This prevents agents from planning against stale or incomplete project state. The `draft` state is a signal: "this task exists in the plan but needs analysis before it can be specified and executed." Because `rhei next` claims without transitioning, the agent has a dedicated phase to do the analysis work before advancing the state.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:273:### Pattern 6: Programmatic State Transitions
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:275:Beyond agent-driven workflows, Rhei plans can be advanced programmatically through the transition callback system. State machines declare `on_leave` and `on_enter` callbacks that fire during transitions — they can approve, reject, or redirect transitions, turning the plan into an executable workflow engine.
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:279:### Pattern 7: Multi-Target Analysis with `all_targets`
docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:281:When the same task should be run once per model and then synthesized, prefer one shared task state with `all_targets` over cloning one state or one task per model. `rhei run` executes the state once per listed target; artifact paths and prompts template on `{target}`, `{target.slug}`, `{agent}`, `{agent.mode}`, and `{model}`. A downstream `summarize` state then consumes the per-target artifacts and writes one final result.
