skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:15:- **Directory Workspace** — an `index.rhei.md` plus a `tasks/` directory of per-file task definitions. Use when multiple agents or humans will work the plan in parallel.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:52:- **Do not author `**Assignee:**` or `> **Result:**` blocks.** Both are runtime-owned: `rhei next` writes `**Assignee:**` when a task is claimed, `rhei complete` removes it and writes `> **Result:** [<id>](runtime/results/<id>.md)`. The plan writer never populates these fields.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:59:Run `rhei states` in the project to discover the allowed state values, their agent instructions, and the declared transitions for the state machine the plan will follow. Use `rhei states --state-machine <path>` to target a specific YAML file (for example, the one referenced by a plan's `**States:**` line), and `rhei states --json` when machine-readable output is preferred. Use only state values reported by that command, follow the printed instructions when describing task work, and respect the declared transitions when choosing initial states.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:68:**State:** `agent-review`
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:75:For state machines that declare a `visits` budget on a state, a counted-visit suffix (`-<n>`, with `n >= 2`) may appear in the rendered state value for later visits. The plan writer normally does not author these — they accumulate at runtime.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:108:Emit a YAML frontmatter block only when the plan needs non-default `structure` settings. The `structure` block is the only thing a plan writer should author in frontmatter; runtime-managed keys under `metadata.tasks.*` (such as `stateVisits` counters) are written by the CLI and must not be hand-authored.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:132:3. Assign only real prerequisites to maximize parallel execution.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:138:   - Existing plan update: preserve truthful terminal states (`completed`, `cancelled`) unless explicitly changed, and preserve any `**Assignee:**` / `> **Result:**` blocks that the runtime has written.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:154:- Do not author `**Assignee:**` or `> **Result:**` — these are runtime-owned.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:164:When the CLI is available, run `rhei validate <plan>` after writing — it performs the full grammar, state, dependency, link, and terminal-coherence checks the checklist only approximates.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:192:- **Too large:** the implementing agent exhausts its context window before finishing.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:194:- **Right-sized:** a task fits comfortably in one agent session and produces a meaningful, reviewable unit of change. Child tasks should decompose work the agent can reuse context for — shared files, related functions, sequential build steps.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:196:The state machine defines what happens at each stage of a task's lifecycle — read it before deciding granularity. A machine with heavyweight review gates (multi-agent review, human sign-off, multi-team handoffs) justifies larger tasks to amortize that overhead. A lightweight machine (implement → done) allows smaller, more focused tasks. Match task size to the cost of moving through the states.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/references/default-states.md:7:Each state carries an instruction for executing agents:
skills/rhei-plan-writer/references/default-states.md:10:- `pending` — Ready for implementation. An `**Assignee:**` on a pending task means work is actively in progress. Implement the task and any child task nodes, logging progress per child task. When implementation is complete and self-tested, either call `rhei complete` to finish directly or transition to `agent-review` when a separate review pass is required.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/references/default-states.md:11:- `agent-review` — A separate reviewing agent inspects the result against the task description, child task nodes, and repository conventions. On pass, transition to `human-review` (or `completed` if no human gate is required). On fail, transition to `agent-review-fix` with concrete findings.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/references/default-states.md:12:- `agent-review-fix` — The implementing agent addresses reviewer findings only — no scope expansion. Transition back to `agent-review` after applying fixes.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/references/default-states.md:13:- `human-review` (gating) — Stop all agent work on this task. Wait for a human to approve, request changes, or edit the plan. Do not transition out of this state autonomously.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/references/default-states.md:14:- `completed` (final) — Treat as immutable. Do not re-open, re-run, or modify unless the user explicitly requests it.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/references/default-states.md:20:- `pending` → `agent-review`, `human-review`, `completed`, `cancelled`
skills/rhei-plan-writer/references/default-states.md:21:- `agent-review` → `agent-review-fix`, `human-review`, `completed`
skills/rhei-plan-writer/references/default-states.md:22:- `agent-review-fix` → `agent-review`, `cancelled`
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:34:6. **Advance state only when the workflow demands it.** Use `rhei transition` for intermediate hops (for example `draft` → `pending`, `agent-review` → `agent-review-fix`). For terminal completion, use `rhei complete` — do not hand-craft a transition into a final state.
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:35:7. **Finalize with `rhei complete`.** When the task is finished, run `rhei complete <plan> --task <id> --result "<one-line summary>"`. The command transitions to the first reachable non-cancelled terminal, appends a `## <from> → <to>` entry plus the message to `runtime/results/<task-id>.md`, links that file via `> **Result:**`, and removes the `**Assignee:**` line.
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:64:rhei transition <plan> --task <id> --from <current-state> --to <target-state>
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:70:- **Compare-and-swap** — `--from` guards against racing workers. If another agent already transitioned the task, the command fails and prints the actual state.
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:73:- **Callbacks** — `on_leave` / `on_enter` callbacks fire on the edge unless `--no-callbacks` is passed.
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:74:- **Result file trail** — each transition appends a `## <from> → <to>` entry to `runtime/results/<task-id>.md`.
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:81:- `pending` → `agent-review` — implementation is complete and self-tested; route to review.
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:82:- `agent-review` → `agent-review-fix` — review found issues; record findings first (see *Agent Review*).
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:83:- `agent-review` → `human-review` — review passed but a human gate is required before completion.
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:84:- `agent-review-fix` → `agent-review` — fixes applied, re-submit for review.
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:87:For terminal completion (`pending` → `completed`, `agent-review` → `completed`, etc.) use `rhei complete`, not `rhei transition`. `rhei complete` picks the first reachable non-cancelled terminal, writes the result file, and unassigns in one atomic step.
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:97:- `rhei transition` leaves it untouched. A long-running task therefore keeps the same assignee across intermediate transitions (for example `pending` → `agent-review` → `agent-review-fix`).
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:104:- State the concrete change: files touched, functions added, commands run to verify.
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:108:When a task re-enters an earlier state (for example `agent-review` → `agent-review-fix` → `agent-review`), append a new paragraph describing the rework rather than rewriting history. If the machine uses counted visits, the re-rendered `**State:** <name>-<n>` line makes the visit explicit — do not edit that suffix by hand.
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:112:When a task enters `agent-review`, the reviewer is a *different* mental mode, not a different person. The reviewer:
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:117:- Chooses the next edge: `agent-review-fix` (rework), `human-review` (needs human), or straight to terminal via `rhei complete` (pass).
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:128:- **Child task state transitions** — child task nodes carry their own mandatory `**State:**` field. For child-only flows in the default machine you may update child states directly in the markdown as you finish each one. After every direct edit, run `rhei validate <plan>` to confirm the file is still well-formed. If the active machine's `node_policy` routes children through a stateful profile that uses the CLI, prefer `rhei transition` / `rhei complete` for children too.
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:129:- **Progress logging** — edit the markdown directly to append per-child progress (see *Progress Logging*). Re-run `rhei validate <plan>` after any direct edit.
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:142:- A task reaches a gating state (typically `human-review`) — stop *that* task but keep working on independent branches of the DAG by re-running `rhei next`.
skills/rhei-plan-worker/SKILL.md:159:This worker flow is distinct from `rhei run` (agent mode). Under `rhei run`, the orchestrator spawns a subprocess for each claimed state and performs the transition after the subprocess exits; the worker skill does the work manually instead.
