     1	# Rhei Agents Specification
     2	
     3	This document specifies how Rhei integrates with coding agents — the CLI tools that execute work on tasks. It covers agent configuration, resolution order, invocation profiles, prompt composition, parallel execution, timeout handling, and log capture.
     4	
     5	For the state machine format see [States Specification](rhei-states.spec.md). For transition callbacks see [Transitions Specification](rhei-transitions.spec.md).
     6	
     7	## Overview
     8	
     9	Rhei can spawn coding agents directly from `rhei run`. Instead of requiring hand-written `workflow.sh` callback scripts, the run command resolves an agent for each task, composes a prompt from the state machine instructions, and spawns the agent as a subprocess. The spawned agent does the work for the current state, writes any required artifacts, and exits. `rhei run` remains the transition authority: after the subprocess exits, the engine evaluates the declared forward transitions and performs the state change itself. Callbacks still fire on transitions — agents and callbacks are complementary.
    10	
    11	## Agent Configuration
    12	
    13	Rhei settings separate **model identity** from **agent transport** and
    14	**tooling**:
    15	
    16	- A **model profile** is the semantic identity used by state machines, callbacks,
    17	  templates, logs, and multi-model execution.
    18	- An **agent profile** is the CLI transport used when `rhei run` spawns an
    19	  autonomous coding agent.
    20	- A model profile names the concrete provider/model pair and may define
    21	  agent-specific launch overrides for autonomous execution.
    22	- An **MCP server profile** describes a Model Context Protocol server the agent
    23	  can connect to for tool access during a state.
    24	- A **skill profile** describes a reusable agent-side prompt/resource bundle
    25	  enabled for a state.
    26	
    27	This separation keeps callback-only workflows model-centric while still letting
    28	`rhei run` resolve the exact subprocess invocation, tool surface, and skill
    29	bundle when agent mode is enabled.
    30	
    31	### Global and Project Settings
    32	
    33	Files:
    34	
    35	- Global: `~/.config/rhei/settings.json`
    36	- Project: `.rhei/settings.json` in the workspace or plan directory
    37	
    38	Both files use the same schema. Project settings compose with global settings by
    39	key rather than replacing the whole file.
    40	
    41	```json
    42	{
    43	  "defaults": {
    44	    "model": "impl-fast",
    45	    "agent": null,
    46	    "agent_mode": "yolo",
    47	    "agent_timeout": "30m",
    48	    "program_timeout": "10m",
    49	    "mcp_servers": [],
    50	    "skills": []
    51	  },
    52	  "agents": {
    53	    "claude-code": {
    54	      "command": ["claude"],
    55	      "prompt_flag": "-p",
    56	      "model_flag": "--model",
    57	      "mcp_config_flag": "--mcp-config",
    58	      "skill_flag": "--skill",
    59	      "stdin_prompt": false,
    60	      "modes": {
    61	        "yolo":   ["--permission-mode", "bypassPermissions"],
    62	        "safe":   ["--permission-mode", "default"],
    63	        "review": ["--permission-mode", "plan"]
    64	      }
    65	    },
    66	    "codex": {
    67	      "command": ["codex", "exec"],
    68	      "model_flag": "--model",
    69	      "mcp_flag": "--mcp",
    70	      "stdin_prompt": true,
    71	      "modes": {
    72	        "yolo": ["--sandbox", "danger-full-access", "--skip-git-repo-check", "-a", "never"],
    73	        "safe": ["--sandbox", "workspace-write"]
    74	      }
    75	    },
    76	    "pi": {
    77	      "command": ["pi"],
    78	      "prompt_flag": "-p",
    79	      "model_flag": "--model",
    80	      "skill_flag": "--skill",
    81	      "stdin_prompt": false
    82	    }
    83	  },
    84	  "models": {
    85	    "impl-fast": {
    86	      "provider": "anthropic",
    87	      "model": "claude-sonnet-4-6",
    88	      "default_agent": "claude-code",
    89	      "agents": {
    90	        "claude-code": {
    91	          "args": ["--permission-mode", "default"],
    92	          "autonomous_args": ["--permission-mode", "bypassPermissions"]
    93	        }
    94	      }
    95	    },
    96	    "review-deep": {
    97	      "provider": "openai",
    98	      "model": "o3",
    99	      "default_agent": "codex",
   100	      "agents": {
   101	        "codex": {
   102	          "args": ["--sandbox", "workspace-write"],
   103	          "autonomous_args": [
   104	            "--sandbox",
   105	            "danger-full-access",
   106	            "--skip-git-repo-check"
   107	          ]
   108	        }
   109	      }
   110	    }
   111	  },
   112	  "mcp_servers": {
   113	    "linear": {
   114	      "command": ["npx", "-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-linear"],
   115	      "env": { "LINEAR_WORKSPACE": "${LINEAR_WORKSPACE}" }
   116	    },
   117	    "postgres": {
   118	      "command": ["mcp-postgres", "--readonly"],
   119	      "env": { "DATABASE_URL": "${DATABASE_URL}" }
   120	    },
   121	    "grafana": {
   122	      "url": "https://grafana.internal/mcp",
   123	      "transport": "sse"
   124	    }
   125	  },
   126	  "skills": {
   127	    "security-review": { "path": "~/.claude/skills/security-review" },
   128	    "test-authoring":  { "path": ".rhei/skills/test-authoring" }
   129	  }
   130	}
   131	```
   132	
   133	#### `defaults`
   134	
   135	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   136	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   137	| `model` | string or null | No | Default model profile id |
   138	| `agent` | string or null | No | Default agent id resolved against the `agents` registry. Inline agent objects are not accepted — define custom agents in `agents.<id>` and reference them here by id. |
   139	| `agent_mode` | string or null | No | Default agent mode (named flag set) applied when a state does not set `agent_mode`. |
   140	| `agent_timeout` | string or null | No | Default autonomous agent timeout |
   141	| `program_timeout` | string or null | No | Default program timeout |
   142	| `mcp_servers` | array | No | Default MCP server entries applied to every agent state. Entries are ids or inline definitions. See [MCP Servers](#mcp-servers). |
   143	| `skills` | array | No | Default skill entries applied to every agent state. Entries are ids or inline definitions. See [Skills](#skills). |
   144	
   145	#### `agents`
   146	
   147	`agents` is a registry of agent transport profiles keyed by agent id. States
   148	and defaults reference agents by id — inline agent definitions are not
   149	permitted on a state or on `defaults.agent`. The registry is the only place an
   150	agent's `command`, flags, and modes are declared.
   151	
   152	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   153	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   154	| `command` | string array | Yes | Base command and fixed arguments |
   155	| `prompt_flag` | string | No | Flag to pass the prompt (e.g., `--prompt`, `-p`). Omit if using stdin. |
   156	| `model_flag` | string | No | Flag to pass the concrete provider model name. Omit if the agent doesn't support model selection. |
   157	| `stdin_prompt` | boolean | No | When `true`, the prompt is piped to stdin instead of passed via flag. Default: `false`. |
   158	| `timeout` | string | No | Default timeout for this agent (e.g., `30m`). Overridden by state-level `agent_timeout`. |
   159	| `mcp_flag` | string | No | Flag used to attach one MCP server per occurrence. `rhei run` emits the flag once per resolved server with a launch spec as its value. Mutually exclusive with `mcp_config_flag`. |
   160	| `mcp_config_flag` | string | No | Flag used to attach a generated MCP config file. `rhei run` writes the resolved set to a temporary JSON file and passes it with this flag once. Mutually exclusive with `mcp_flag`. |
   161	| `skill_flag` | string | No | Flag used to enable one skill per occurrence. `rhei run` emits the flag once per resolved skill id. Omit to declare the agent does not support skills. |
   162	| `modes` | object | No | Named flag sets, keyed by mode name. Values are ordered string arrays appended to the command at spawn time. See [Modes](#modes). |
   163	
   164	Built-in agent ids (see [Known Agent Profiles](#known-agent-profiles)) are
   165	preloaded as the default agents registry. A user entry with the same id in
   166	global or project settings replaces the built-in entry wholesale — `command`,
   167	flags, and `modes` are taken from the user entry without field-level merging.
   168	
   169	#### `models`
   170	
   171	`models` is a registry of named model profiles keyed by model id.
   172	
   173	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   174	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   175	| `provider` | string | Yes | Provider identifier such as `openai` or `anthropic` |
   176	| `model` | string | Yes | Concrete provider model name such as `o3` or `claude-sonnet-4-6` |
   177	| `default_agent` | string | No | Preferred agent id when `rhei run` needs to spawn this model autonomously |
   178	| `agents` | object | No | Per-agent launch overrides for this model, keyed by agent id |
   179	
   180	Each `models.<id>.agents.<agent-id>` binding has this shape:
   181	
   182	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   183	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   184	| `args` | string array | No | Additional agent arguments for normal/inherited invocation |
   185	| `autonomous_args` | string array | No | Arguments preferred by `rhei run` when launching autonomously |
   186	| `timeout` | string | No | Timeout default specific to this model-agent binding |
   187	
   188	#### `mcp_servers`
   189	
   190	`mcp_servers` is a registry of named MCP server profiles keyed by server id.
   191	Entries describe how to launch or connect to a Model Context Protocol server
   192	so it can be attached to an agent subprocess.
   193	
   194	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   195	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   196	| `command` | string array | One of `command` / `url` | Command and arguments to launch a local MCP server |
   197	| `url` | string | One of `command` / `url` | URL of a remote MCP server. Requires `transport`. |
   198	| `transport` | string | No | Transport for remote servers. Supported values: `sse`, `websocket`. Ignored for `command`-based servers. |
   199	| `env` | object | No | Environment variables for the server process. Values may reference host environment with `${VAR}` syntax. Only meaningful for `command`-based servers. |
   200	| `working_directory` | string | No | Working directory for the server process. Only meaningful for `command`-based servers. |
   201	| `startup_timeout` | string | No | Maximum time to wait for the server to complete its MCP handshake after launch. Duration format (`30s`, `10s`, …). Default: `10s`. |
   202	
   203	`command` and `url` are mutually exclusive. An entry must declare exactly one.
   204	
   205	#### `skills`
   206	
   207	`skills` is a registry of named skill profiles keyed by skill id. Each entry
   208	identifies an agent-side skill bundle that should be enabled for states that
   209	list it.
   210	
   211	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   212	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   213	| `path` | string | Yes | Filesystem path to the skill bundle. Leading `~` expands to the user's home directory. |
   214	| `description` | string | No | Human-readable description of the skill's purpose. |
   215	
   216	Skills are agent-specific capabilities. A resolved skill is wired to the agent
   217	only when the resolved agent profile declares a `skill_flag`; otherwise the
   218	skill is skipped with a warning (see [Missing Tooling](#missing-tooling)). This
   219	keeps state machines portable across agents that do not implement skills.
   220	
   221	### Per-State Settings
   222	
   223	The `target` / `all_targets` fields are the preferred execution selectors on
   224	state definitions in `states.yaml`. The legacy `model` / `all_models`,
   225	optional `agent`, `mcp_servers`, and `skills` fields remain supported for
   226	compatibility. See
   227	[States Specification — Agent Field](rhei-states.spec.md#agent-field) and
   228	[States Specification — MCP Servers and Skills](rhei-states.spec.md#mcp-servers-and-skills).
   229	
   230	### Merge Semantics
   231	
   232	Built-in agents load first, global settings compose over them, then project
   233	settings compose over the result:
   234	
   235	- `defaults` shallow-override by field.
   236	- `agents` merge by agent id. A user entry with the same id as a built-in or a
   237	  global entry **replaces that entry wholesale** — there is no field-level
   238	  merge within a single agent entry. To tweak just one mode of a built-in
   239	  agent, redeclare the whole entry.
   240	- `models` merge by model id.
   241	- `models.<id>.agents` merge by agent id.
   242	- `mcp_servers` merge by server id.
   243	- `skills` merge by skill id.
   244	- `null` explicitly clears an inherited optional field.
   245	
   246	`defaults.mcp_servers` and `defaults.skills` are replaced wholesale by the
   247	project list when the project defines them, not concatenated. Use an empty
   248	array (`"mcp_servers": []`) to clear inherited defaults, or repeat entries
   249	explicitly to extend them. This keeps the precedence predictable — every
   250	level's effective tooling default is the one written there.
   251	
   252	This lets a project override only a model's concrete provider/model pair or
   253	only a model-agent binding's autonomous arguments without redefining unrelated
   254	global entries.
   255	
   256	### Resolution Order
   257	
   258	When `rhei run` or a callback needs model context for a task in a given state,
   259	it resolves the model id in this order:
   260	

 succeeded in 370ms:
   260	
   261	1. **CLI override** — `--model <MODEL>`
   262	2. **State-level** — `model` on the state definition in `states.yaml`
   263	3. **Project defaults** — `.rhei/settings.json` `defaults.model`
   264	4. **Global defaults** — `~/.config/rhei/settings.json` `defaults.model`
   265	
   266	The resolved model id must exist in the merged `models` registry. If no model
   267	is configured at any level, model-specific callback and template fields are
   268	omitted.
   269	
   270	When `rhei run` is launching an autonomous agent, it resolves the agent id in
   271	this order:
   272	
   273	1. **CLI override** — `--agent <AGENT>`
   274	2. **State-level** — `agent` on the state definition in `states.yaml`
   275	3. **Project defaults** — `.rhei/settings.json` `defaults.agent`
   276	4. **Global defaults** — `~/.config/rhei/settings.json` `defaults.agent`
   277	5. **Model default** — `models.<id>.default_agent`
   278	
   279	The resolved id must match an entry in the merged `agents` registry
   280	(built-ins → global → project). An id with no matching entry is a
   281	configuration error:
   282	
   283	```
   284	error: agent 'my-agent' is not defined. Add an entry to agents.<id> in
   285	.rhei/settings.json or ~/.config/rhei/settings.json, or reference one of the
   286	built-in ids (claude-code, codex, cursor, gemini, kilocode).
   287	```
   288	
   289	If no agent is configured at any level and the resolved model does not declare
   290	a `default_agent`, `rhei run` fails:
   291	
   292	```
   293	error: no agent configured for model 'impl-fast'.
   294	Set defaults.agent, the state's agent, models.impl-fast.default_agent, or pass --agent <AGENT> to rhei run.
   295	```
   296	
   297	For a state that declares `all_targets`, this resolution is bypassed for the
   298	fields encoded directly in each selector: the agent id, optional mode, optional
   299	provider, and model name come from the selector itself. Validation must still
   300	verify that the referenced agent exists and that any referenced mode exists on
   301	that agent. For the legacy `all_models` form, agent resolution still runs
   302	independently for each model-specific execution of the state through the normal
   303	order above.
   304	
   305	#### Mode Resolution Order
   306	
   307	When the resolved agent declares `modes`, `rhei run` picks one at spawn time:
   308	
   309	1. **CLI override** — `--agent-mode <MODE>`
   310	2. **State-level** — `agent_mode` on the state definition in `states.yaml`
   311	3. **Project defaults** — `.rhei/settings.json` `defaults.agent_mode`
   312	4. **Global defaults** — `~/.config/rhei/settings.json` `defaults.agent_mode`
   313	5. **Registry default** — the first declared mode in the agent entry's
   314	   `modes` map
   315	6. **None** — if the agent entry has no `modes`, no mode flags are appended
   316	
   317	The resolved mode name must be a key in the agent entry's `modes` map when
   318	the map is non-empty. A missing mode is a spawn-time error.
   319	
   320	When `rhei run` composes the tool surface for a state, it resolves the
   321	effective MCP server and skill sets:
   322	
   323	1. Start from `defaults.mcp_servers` (and `defaults.skills`) as resolved by the
   324	   merged settings.
   325	2. Union with the state's `mcp_servers` (and `skills`) list, if any. An empty
   326	   list on the state clears the defaults for that state.
   327	3. Deduplicate by id. Within a single effective set, later entries for the same
   328	   id override earlier ones — a state-level override wins over a defaults
   329	   entry.
   330	4. Resolve each id against the merged `mcp_servers` / `skills` registry. Inline
   331	   object entries on the state (or in `defaults`) do not require a registry
   332	   entry; they are used as-is.
   333	5. An id with no registry match and no inline definition is a validation
   334	   error.
   335	
   336	The resolved sets are distinct per state and per invocation. Changing the
   337	current state or restarting `rhei run` recomputes them.
   338	
   339	### Partial Overrides
   340	
   341	Each level can override model and agent independently:
   342	
   343	```yaml
   344	# states.yaml — state overrides only the model profile
   345	states:
   346	  agent-review:
   347	    model: review-deep
   348	```
   349	
   350	```json
   351	// .rhei/settings.json — project sets the default agent transport
   352	{
   353	  "defaults": {
   354	    "agent": "codex"
   355	  }
   356	}
   357	```
   358	
   359	Result for `agent-review`: model=`review-deep` (from state), agent=`codex`
   360	(from project defaults unless `review-deep.default_agent` or a CLI override
   361	supersedes it).
   362	
   363	## Known Agent Profiles
   364	
   365	Rhei ships with built-in invocation profiles for known coding agents. Each
   366	profile defines how to spawn the agent, deliver the prompt, pass the concrete
   367	provider model name, and set transport-level defaults. Each built-in also
   368	declares a `yolo` mode carrying the autonomous/dangerous flag set that was
   369	historically the agent's default.
   370	
   371	| Agent ID | Binary | Prompt Delivery | Model Flag | MCP Wiring | Skill Wiring | `yolo` Mode Flags |
   372	|----------|--------|-----------------|------------|------------|--------------|-------------------|
   373	| `claude-code` | `claude` | `-p <prompt>` | `--model <m>` | `--mcp-config <path>` | `--skill <id>` | `--permission-mode bypassPermissions` |
   374	| `codex` | `codex exec` | `--` (stdin) | `--model <m>` | `--mcp <spec>` (per server) | unsupported | `--sandbox danger-full-access --skip-git-repo-check` |
   375	| `gemini` | `gemini` | `--prompt <prompt>` | `--model <m>` | unsupported | unsupported | `--approval-mode yolo` |
   376	| `cursor` | `cursor-agent` | `--print <prompt>` | `--model <m>` | unsupported | unsupported | `--force` |
   377	| `kilocode` | `kilo` | positional via `--auto <prompt>` | `--model <m>` | unsupported | unsupported | `--yolo` |
   378	| `pi` | `pi` | `-p <prompt>` | `--model <m>` | unsupported | `--skill <path>` | (no modes — pi has no permission layer; isolate at the sandbox/container level) |
   379	
   380	The agent IDs match those used by `rhei install-skills --agent`.
   381	
   382	Agents marked `unsupported` for MCP or skills receive a warning at spawn time
   383	when the resolved state's effective set includes entries they cannot consume.
   384	Required MCP entries (see [Missing Tooling](#missing-tooling)) escalate the
   385	warning to an error.
   386	
   387	A user-written entry for one of these ids in `settings.json` replaces the
   388	built-in entry wholesale (see [Merge Semantics](#merge-semantics)).
   389	
   390	### Custom Agents
   391	
   392	When the built-in profiles don't fit, declare a new agent in the `agents`
   393	registry — **never inline** on a state or on `defaults.agent`:
   394	
   395	```json
   396	{
   397	  "agents": {
   398	    "my-agent": {
   399	      "command": ["my-agent", "--autonomous"],
   400	      "prompt_flag": "--prompt",
   401	      "model_flag": "--model",
   402	      "stdin_prompt": false,
   403	      "modes": {
   404	        "yolo": ["--permissions", "full"],
   405	        "safe": ["--permissions", "read-only"]
   406	      }
   407	    }
   408	  }
   409	}
   410	```
   411	
   412	States and defaults then reference the agent by id:
   413	
   414	```yaml
   415	states:
   416	  pending:
   417	    agent: my-agent
   418	    agent_mode: yolo
   419	```
   420	
   421	```json
   422	{
   423	  "defaults": {
   424	    "agent": "my-agent",
   425	    "agent_mode": "safe"
   426	  }
   427	}
   428	```
   429	
   430	Inline agent objects are rejected by the validator. This keeps state
   431	machines portable — the transport surface lives in `settings.json` where a
   432	project or a user can replace it without touching `states.yaml`.
   433	
   434	### Modes
   435	
   436	A mode is a named ordered list of extra CLI flags. When `rhei run` spawns the
   437	agent, the resolved mode's flags are appended right after the base
   438	`command`, before the prompt and model flags. The full flag order is:
   439	
   440	```
   441	<command...> <mode flags...> <prompt_flag> <prompt>? <model_flag> <model>? <mcp/skill flags...>
   442	```
   443	
   444	(When `stdin_prompt` is `true`, the prompt is written to stdin instead of
   445	being passed via `prompt_flag`, and `--` is appended after the model flag so
   446	agents like `codex exec --` get a clean positional-arg separator.)
   447	
   448	Mode names are free-form. `yolo` is a widely-used convention for
   449	"autonomous, dangerous posture"; `safe`, `review`, `plan`, and `audit` are
   450	other common choices. Rhei does not interpret mode names — it only injects
   451	the named flag list.
   452	
   453	An agent entry may declare zero, one, or many modes. When no modes are
   454	declared, no mode flags are appended and `agent_mode` must not be set for
   455	states that use this agent. See
   456	[Mode Resolution Order](#mode-resolution-order) for how a mode is selected.
   457	
   458	## Prompt Composition
   459	
   460	When `rhei run` spawns an agent for a task, it composes a prompt from the state machine definition and the task content. The prompt has this structure:
   461	
   462	```
   463	# Task {task_id}: {task_title}
   464	
   465	## State: {state}
   466	
   467	{resolved personality, if present}
   468	
   469	## Instructions
   470	
   471	{resolved instructions from state definition}
   472	
   473	## Task Content
   474	
   475	{task body from the plan, including any child task nodes}
   476	
   477	## Rhei Commands
   478	
   479	You are working in a rhei-managed plan at `{plan_path}`.
   480	The `rhei run` process that spawned you is responsible for advancing the task after you exit successfully.
   481	Do not run `rhei transition` or `rhei complete` from this spawned agent process unless the workflow explicitly instructs you to launch a nested or delegated execution that manages its own state independently.
   482	
   483	Available transitions from `{state}`:
   484	{list of declared transitions from current state, with descriptions}
   485	```
   486	
   487	The prompt carries domain instructions only. It does not contain completion
   488	prose such as "create every required output artifact and then exit":
   489	completion is enforced by the state's [Completion Condition](#completion-condition),
   490	not by prompt wording. Required artifact paths are already visible to the agent
   491	via resolved `{output.<name>.path}` variables in the state's `instructions`,
   492	and every supported agent exits deterministically after one turn in its native
   493	headless mode.
   494	
   495	Template variables (`{task_id}`, `{model}`, `{model.provider}`,
   496	`{model.name}`, `{visit_count}`, etc.) are resolved before the prompt is sent,
   497	using the same resolution rules as `rhei next`. See [Template Variables](rhei-states.spec.md#template-variables-in-instructions-and-personality).
   498	
   499	The prompt is delivered to the agent via its configured prompt delivery mechanism (flag or stdin).
   500	
   501	### Completion Authority
   502	
   503	Every state has a **completion authority** — the role that decides when the
   504	state's work is done and drives the resulting transition. Rhei defines two
   505	authorities; exactly one applies to any given execution of a state.
   506	
   507	| Authority | Applies when | Transition driver |
   508	|-----------|--------------|-------------------|
   509	| `worker` | The invoking role is a manual worker (human, `rhei-plan-worker` skill session, or direct `rhei next` / `rhei transition` / `rhei complete` caller). | The worker calls `rhei transition` or `rhei complete`. |
   510	| `orchestrator` | `rhei run` has spawned the agent or program for this state. | `rhei run` evaluates the state's [Completion Condition](#completion-condition), then selects and executes the matching forward transition. |
   511	
   512	Completion authority is determined by the execution mode, not declared on the
   513	state. The same state definition is legal under both authorities. This is what
   514	lets a plan be driven either agent-by-agent (manual workers) or end-to-end
   515	(`rhei run`) without rewriting `states.yaml`.
   516	
   517	Normative rules:
   518	
   519	- Under `worker` authority, the worker owns both the work and the transition.
   520	  `rhei run` is not involved.
   521	- Under `orchestrator` authority, the spawned subprocess owns the work;
   522	  `rhei run` owns the transition. The subprocess must not call
   523	  `rhei transition` or `rhei complete`, and must not edit `**State:**` lines
   524	  directly. The one exception is a nested execution started from within the
   525	  agent, which manages its own state independently of the outer `rhei run`.
   526	- `instructions` and `personality` describe domain work only. They must not
   527	  describe how or when to stop, whether to call transition commands, or how
   528	  completion is detected. Those are properties of the execution model, not of
   529	  the state.
   530	- Gating states (`gating: true`) bypass completion authority: no subprocess is
   531	  spawned and no automatic transition fires.
   532	
   533	This separation keeps state transitions serialized through one orchestrator
   534	even when many agents run in parallel.
   535	
   536	### Completion Condition
   537	
   538	When completion authority is `orchestrator`, `rhei run` decides deterministically
   539	when the state's work is complete. The completion condition is a property of
   540	the state machine and the execution mode, not of the prompt — so the same
   541	determinism applies to every execution of that state regardless of which agent
   542	is resolved.
   543	
   544	The condition is normative and universal for agent states:
   545	
   546	1. The subprocess exits with code `0`, **and**
   547	2. Every required artifact declared in the state's `outputs:` list exists on disk.
   548	
   549	Both are evaluated after the process exits. If the state declares no `outputs:`,
   550	condition (2) is vacuously true and exit alone suffices.
   551	
   552	This contract maps 1:1 onto the native headless mode of every supported agent.
   553	All six built-ins — `claude-code -p`, `codex exec`, `gemini --prompt --yolo`,
   554	`cursor-agent --print --force`, `kilo --auto --yolo`, and `pi -p` — run one
   555	turn-loop and exit. Rhei detects completion from process exit plus declared
   556	output artifacts; no cross-agent stop signal, sentinel file, or "done" RPC is
   557	defined or needed.
   558	
   559	Program states have their own exit-code-driven completion semantics documented
   560	in [Program States Specification](rhei-programs.spec.md#exit-code-transitions);

 succeeded in 530ms:
     1	# `rhei run`
     2	
     3	Drive a plan end-to-end by repeatedly claiming the next ready task, spawning the state's agent or program, waiting for completion, and performing the resulting transition. `rhei run` operates under `orchestrator` authority: the orchestrator — not the spawned subprocess — owns every state transition. See [Agents Specification — Completion Authority](rhei-agents.spec.md#completion-authority) for the full authority contract.
     4	
     5	This document specifies the command contract and execution loop. The live terminal UI is specified separately in [rhei-run-tui.spec.md](rhei-run-tui.spec.md).
     6	
     7	## Usage
     8	
     9	```bash
    10	rhei run <RHEI_PLAN_OR_WORKSPACE> [flags]
    11	```
    12	
    13	## Options
    14	
    15	Flags are grouped by concern:
    16	
    17	### Standalone
    18	
    19	| Flag                     | Default | Description                                                                |
    20	|--------------------------|---------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------|
    21	| `--dry-run`              | false   | Print the sequence of transitions that would be made without executing them |
    22	| `--no-callbacks`         | false   | Skip execution of `on_leave` / `on_enter` callbacks                        |
    23	| `--continue-on-error`    | false   | Continue to the next task when an agent or program exits non-zero          |
    24	| `--parallel <N>`         | 1       | Maximum number of agents or programs to run concurrently (0 = unlimited)   |
    25	| `--tui`                  | auto    | Force TUI mode even when stdout is not detected as a TTY                   |
    26	| `--no-tui`               | auto    | Force plain stdout output even when stdout is a TTY                        |
    27	
    28	### Agent Execution
    29	
    30	| Flag                    | Description                                                             |
    31	|-------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------|
    32	| `--no-agent`            | Disable agent spawning; use callback-only advancement                   |
    33	| `--agent <AGENT>`       | Override the agent for this run                                         |
    34	| `--agent-mode <MODE>`   | Override the agent mode (named flag set) for this run                   |
    35	| `--model <MODEL>`       | Override the model for this run                                         |
    36	
    37	### Program Execution
    38	
    39	| Flag                           | Description                                                                      |
    40	|--------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
    41	| `--no-program`                 | Disable program spawning; use callback-only advancement for program states       |
    42	| `--program-timeout <DURATION>` | Override the program timeout for this run (applied per program state)            |
    43	
    44	## Execution Loop
    45	
    46	`rhei run` runs passes until no further forward progress is possible:
    47	
    48	Mode selection: `rhei run` uses orchestrated subprocess execution whenever any reachable non-terminal, non-gating state declares autonomous work via `program`, `agent`, `target`, `all_targets`, `model`, or `all_models`. Callback-only advancement is entered only when no such state exists, or when the caller explicitly disables spawning with `--no-agent` and/or `--no-program`. If a state declares model/target-driven work but no agent transport resolves, `rhei run` fails with a missing-agent configuration error; it does not silently fall back to callback-only transitions for that state.
    49	
    50	1. Load the state machine and plan. Validate.
    51	2. Scan all tasks and compute the *ready set*: tasks whose `**Prior:**` are all in terminal states, whose current state is non-terminal and non-gating, and whose current state's required `inputs:` all exist. Tasks whose current state declares `poll:` and whose `metadata.tasks.<id>.pollNextAttemptAt.<state-name>` is later than the current wall-clock time are excluded from the ready set until the interval elapses. See [Next Command](rhei-next.spec.md#default-behavior-claim-mode) for the full claimability rule and [Polling States](#polling-states) for the poll scheduling rule.
    52	3. Up to `--parallel` tasks from the ready set are executed concurrently, subject to the [concurrent-state rule](#parallel-execution): at most one ready task per non-concurrent state is scheduled per pass. For each task:
    53	   - Resolve the state's target: either an agent subprocess (`agent` or resolved target selector) or a program (`program`).
    54	   - Spawn the subprocess with the state's resolved instructions, environment (`RHEI_*` variables defined in [Agents Specification — Environment Variables](rhei-agents.spec.md#environment-variables)), and timeout.
    55	   - Wait for the subprocess to exit or for the timeout to fire. On timeout, send `SIGTERM`, grace 10 s, then `SIGKILL`.
    56	4. On subprocess exit, evaluate the state's [Completion Condition](rhei-agents.spec.md#completion-condition): exit code `0` plus every required `outputs:` artifact present on disk.
    57	5. If the condition holds, select the first declared transition whose `condition` / `exit_code` matches and execute it. The subprocess **must not** call `rhei transition` or `rhei complete`; the orchestrator owns the transition.
    58	6. If the condition fails (non-zero exit or missing outputs), route through the state's error or timeout transition per [Agents Specification — Execution Loop](rhei-agents.spec.md#execution-loop). When no error transition is declared and `--continue-on-error` is unset, `rhei run` aborts with a non-zero exit code.
    59	7. Repeat until no pass makes progress. Exit `0` when the plan reaches a state where every task is terminal. Exit non-zero when progress halts with non-terminal tasks remaining and no further advancement is possible.
    60	
    61	`rhei run` does not transition out of [gating states](rhei-states.spec.md#per-state-fields) — exiting one requires an explicit human-initiated `rhei transition` call.
    62	
    63	Gating states are a barrier, not an immediate global abort. If one task enters a
    64	gating state while other non-gating tasks are already running, or while other
    65	independent non-gating tasks remain ready, `rhei run` lets that remaining
    66	non-gating work finish. The run halts for human input only when the remaining
    67	non-terminal tasks are either themselves in gating states or blocked behind a
    68	gating dependency. In other words: a gate waits for everyone else to complete,
    69	then stops autonomous progress at the boundary.
    70	
    71	## Dry Run
    72	
    73	With `--dry-run`, `rhei run` performs the same scan and selection logic but prints each planned transition instead of executing subprocesses or callbacks. Output format:
    74	
    75	```text
    76	would transition: Task <ID>  <from> -> <to>
    77	```
    78	
    79	No file lock is acquired, no markdown is rewritten, and no runtime artifacts are created.
    80	
    81	## Parallel Execution
    82	
    83	With `--parallel N`, up to `N` subprocesses run concurrently. The orchestrator:
    84	
    85	- Assigns each spawn a slot index.
    86	- Writes one line to `runtime/transitions.log` per `SlotAssigned` and one per `SlotReleased`; see [Run TUI Specification — Transition Journal](rhei-run-tui.spec.md#transition-journal).
    87	- Serializes every state write through its own file lock, so two agents completing at once cannot corrupt the plan.
    88	
    89	Tasks whose transitions would race on the same task node are never scheduled in parallel: scheduling is driven by the ready set, which excludes tasks already in flight.
    90	
    91	### Polling States
    92	
    93	States that declare a [`poll:`](rhei-states.spec.md#polling-states) block are time-triggered: each attempt spawns one subprocess, the engine evaluates transitions, and a self-loop transition means "retry after `poll.interval`". Between attempts, the orchestrator:
    94	
    95	- Persists `metadata.tasks.<id>.pollNextAttemptAt.<state-name> = now() + interval` and `metadata.tasks.<id>.stateVisits.<state-name>` (the attempt counter).
    96	- Releases the `--parallel` slot so other ready tasks may run.
    97	- Does not hold a timer thread; the next pass re-scans and picks the task up again only once `pollNextAttemptAt` is in the past.
    98	
    99	If, at the end of a pass, every remaining non-terminal task is either in a gating state, blocked behind a gating dependency, or blocked by a pending `pollNextAttemptAt`, `rhei run` sleeps until the earliest `pollNextAttemptAt` across all blocked poll tasks (bounded below by 1 s to avoid busy-looping) and then begins a new pass. If no poll deadline is pending and only gating remains, the run exits as it does today.
   100	
   101	Once `stateVisits.<state-name>` reaches `poll.max_attempts`, the engine refuses to select a self-loop transition and picks the first matching non-self-loop instead. If no non-self-loop transition matches, the run halts that task with a "polling exhausted with no matching non-self-loop transition" error — `--continue-on-error` applies as with any other task failure. A non-self-loop exit at any attempt clears both `pollNextAttemptAt.<state-name>` and `stateVisits.<state-name>`.
   102	
   103	### Concurrent vs. Serial States
   104	
   105	The [`concurrent`](rhei-states.spec.md#per-state-fields) flag on a `StateDef` determines whether multiple ready tasks in the same state may be scheduled together in one pass:
   106	
   107	- `concurrent: true` — any number of ready tasks in this state may be scheduled together (bounded by `--parallel`).
   108	- `concurrent: false` (the default) — at most one ready task in this state is scheduled per pass. Additional tasks remain ready and are picked up on the next pass.
   109	
   110	The flag does not change state entry/exit semantics or transitions, and it does not affect within-task fanout (`all_targets` / `all_models`): every resolved invocation for a single scheduled task is still spawned together.
   111	
   112	## Relationship to Other Commands
   113	
   114	`rhei run` drives the full plan forward under orchestrator authority. It is mutually exclusive per execution with the manual-worker flow (`next` / `transition` / `complete`) — they never overlap on the same task because `rhei run` holds transition responsibility for the states it drives.
   115	
   116	See [How Rhei Is Used — Command Surface](rhei-usage.spec.md#command-surface) for the full table comparing all five coordination commands.
   117	
