   562	state also declares `outputs:`.
   563	
   564	#### Runtime Semantics
   565	
   566	Under `orchestrator` authority, `rhei run`:
   567	
   568	1. Spawns the subprocess and waits on `(subprocess exit) OR (timeout fires)`.
   569	2. On timeout, sends `SIGTERM` to the subprocess, 10 s grace, then `SIGKILL`.
   570	   Timeout transitions fire per [Timeout Handling](#timeout-handling). Agents
   571	   that fork long-running descendants should install their own cleanup; the
   572	   engine kills only the direct subprocess.
   573	3. On non-zero exit, routes through the exit-code / error transition path
   574	   documented in the [Execution Loop](#execution-loop). The artifact check is
   575	   skipped.
   576	4. On exit code `0`:
   577	   - Verify every required output artifact exists.
   578	   - If any is missing, the task stays in its current state and the engine
   579	     logs `warning: agent exited 0 but required outputs are missing for task
   580	     {id} in state '{state}': <name1>, <name2>`. No transition fires.
   581	   - Otherwise, evaluate forward transitions in normal selection order and
   582	     execute the first match.
   583	
   584	#### Timeout Requirement
   585	
   586	Under `orchestrator` authority, a timeout must resolve to a finite value
   587	through the chain documented in [Timeout Handling](#timeout-handling). States
   588	that resolve to no timeout at any level are a validation error under
   589	`orchestrator` authority. Under `worker` authority there is no timeout
   590	enforcement.
   591	
   592	This closes the one remaining non-determinism in the completion contract: an
   593	agent that hangs without producing outputs is bounded by the timeout and
   594	routed to the state's timeout transition (or fails the task with a warning
   595	when no timeout transition is declared).
   596	
   597	## Environment Variables
   598	
   599	The agent subprocess inherits these environment variables, consistent with the
   600	callback environment:
   601	
   602	| Variable | Value |
   603	|----------|-------|
   604	| `RHEI_PLAN_PATH` | Absolute path to the plan file or workspace directory |
   605	| `RHEI_TASK_ID` | Current task identifier |
   606	| `RHEI_STATE` | Current state name |
   607	| `RHEI_MODEL` | Model profile id, if configured |
   608	| `RHEI_MODEL_PROVIDER` | Resolved provider id, if configured |
   609	| `RHEI_MODEL_NAME` | Resolved provider model name, if configured |
   610	| `RHEI_AGENT` | Agent identifier, if configured |
   611	| `RHEI_MCP_SERVERS` | Comma-separated list of resolved MCP server ids that started successfully. Empty when none are attached. |
   612	| `RHEI_MCP_<NAME>_AVAILABLE` | `true` or `false` for each declared MCP server in the state's effective set. `<NAME>` is the server id uppercased with hyphens and spaces replaced by underscores. |
   613	| `RHEI_SKILLS` | Comma-separated list of resolved skill ids enabled for this state. Empty when none are attached. |
   614	| `RHEI_SKILL_<ID>_AVAILABLE` | `true` or `false` for each declared skill in the state's effective set. `<ID>` follows the same transformation as MCP names. |
   615	
   616	The agent's working directory is set to the workspace root (for directory workspaces) or the plan file's parent directory (for single-file plans).
   617	
   618	## `rhei run` — Agent Mode
   619	
   620	### CLI
   621	
   622	```
   623	rhei run <RHEI_PLAN> [--dry-run] [--no-callbacks] [--no-agent] [--no-program]
   624	                     [--agent <AGENT>] [--model <MODEL>] [--continue-on-error]
   625	                     [--parallel <N>] [--program-timeout <DURATION>]
   626	```
   627	
   628	| Flag | Default | Description |
   629	|------|---------|-------------|
   630	| `--dry-run` | false | Show what would be spawned without executing |
   631	| `--no-callbacks` | false | Skip `on_leave`/`on_enter` callbacks |
   632	| `--no-agent` | false | Disable agent spawning; fall back to callback-only advancement (pre-agent behavior) |
   633	| `--no-program` | false | Disable program spawning; fall back to callback-only advancement for program states |
   634	| `--agent <AGENT>` | | Override the agent transport for this run |
   635	| `--model <MODEL>` | | Override the model profile id for this run |
   636	| `--continue-on-error` | false | Continue to the next task when an agent or program exits non-zero |
   637	| `--parallel <N>` | 1 | Maximum number of agents/programs to run concurrently. `0` means unlimited. |
   638	| `--program-timeout <DURATION>` | | Override program timeout for this run (e.g., `10m`, `1h`). See [Program States Specification](rhei-programs.spec.md#timeout-handling). |
   639	
   640	### Execution Loop
   641	
   642	#### Sequential Mode (default, `--parallel 1`)
   643	
   644	1. Load plan and state machine. Validate.
   645	2. Find the next claimable task (same eligibility as `rhei next`).
   646	3. Resolve the model and, if agent mode is enabled, the agent for the task's current state (resolution order above).
   647	4. If agent mode is enabled and no agent is configured, fail with an error.
   648	5. Compose the prompt (see [Prompt Composition](#prompt-composition)).
   649	6. Log the spawn to `runtime/logs/task-{task_id}-{state}[-{visit_count}].log`.
   650	7. Spawn the agent CLI as a subprocess with the composed prompt.
   651	8. Wait for the agent process to exit (subject to timeout — see [Timeout Handling](#timeout-handling)).
   652	9. Re-read the plan. If some external actor changed the task's state while the agent was running, respect that authoritative plan state and continue the loop from there.
   653	10. Otherwise, if the agent exited `0`, evaluate the current state's declared forward transitions in normal transition-selection order. If one transition matches, `rhei run` executes it and logs the resulting state change.
   654	11. If the agent exited `0` and no forward transition matches, log a warning: `warning: agent exited 0 but task {id} did not advance from '{state}'`. Continue to the next task.
   655	12. If the agent exited non-zero:
   656	    - Without `--continue-on-error`: log the error and stop.
   657	    - With `--continue-on-error`: log the error, skip this task, continue.
   658	13. Repeat until no claimable tasks remain or all tasks are terminal.
   659	
   660	#### Parallel Mode (`--parallel N` where N > 1 or N = 0)
   661	
   662	1. Load plan and state machine. Validate.
   663	2. Find all claimable tasks (same eligibility as `rhei next`, but collect all candidates).
   664	3. Select up to N tasks that are mutually independent (no dependency edges between them). When N = 0, select all independent claimable tasks.
   665	4. For each selected task, resolve the model and agent, compose the prompt, and spawn the agent subprocess concurrently. Each agent writes to its own log file and is treated as a worker for the task's current state, not as a transition authority.
   666	5. Wait for any agent to exit (timeout or completion).
   667	6. When an agent exits:
   668	   a. Re-read the plan.
   669	   b. Process the result using the same rules as sequential mode: if an external actor already changed the task state, respect it; otherwise, on exit `0`, let `rhei run` evaluate and execute the next matching forward transition; on non-zero exit, apply the error path.
   670	   c. Scan for newly claimable tasks (dependencies may have been unblocked).
   671	   d. If new tasks are claimable and the pool is below N, spawn agents for them.
   672	7. Repeat until no claimable tasks remain or all tasks are terminal.
   673	
   674	**Independence rule:** Two tasks are independent when neither appears in the other's transitive `**Prior:**` chain. The engine must not spawn two agents that could produce conflicting edits to the same task file. For directory workspaces, each task lives in a separate file, so file conflicts are avoided by construction.
   675	
   676	**Single-file plans:** Parallel mode is limited to `--parallel 1` for single-file plans because agents could produce conflicting edits to the same file. `rhei run` prints a warning if `--parallel` > 1 is requested with a single-file plan and falls back to sequential execution.
   677	
   678	### Interaction Between Agents and Callbacks
   679	
   680	Agents and callbacks are complementary, not exclusive:
   681	
   682	- **Agent** does the work of the current state (coding, reviewing, fixing, writing artifacts).
   683	- **`rhei run`** evaluates success or failure and performs the state transition.
   684	- **Callbacks** handle side effects of that transition (creating artifacts, spawning tasks, notifying systems).
   685	
   686	When `rhei run` is in agent mode:
   687	1. The agent is spawned for the current state.
   688	2. The agent performs work and exits.
   689	3. `rhei run` selects and executes the transition.
   690	4. `on_leave` / `on_enter` callbacks fire as part of that engine-driven transition.
   691	
   692	`--no-callbacks` suppresses callbacks but not agent or program spawning. `--no-agent` suppresses agent spawning but not program spawning or callbacks. `--no-program` suppresses program spawning but not agent spawning or callbacks. All three can be combined independently.
   693	
   694	### Gating States
   695	
   696	When a task reaches a gating state (`gating: true`), `rhei run` does not spawn an agent. Instead it logs:
   697	
   698	```
   699	Task {id} is in gating state '{state}'. Waiting for human action.
   700	```
   701	
   702	The task is skipped and the engine continues with other claimable tasks. When the human transitions the task out of the gating state (via `rhei transition`), the next run pass picks it up.
   703	
   704	## Missing Tooling
   705	
   706	Tooling — MCP servers and skills — can fail to be available for reasons that
   707	only surface at spawn time: a binary is not on `PATH`, a remote MCP URL is
   708	unreachable, an env var is unset, or a skill path does not exist. Rhei
   709	distinguishes three failure classes:
   710	
   711	| Failure | When detected | Default behavior |
   712	|---------|---------------|------------------|
   713	| Id referenced in a state but not in the merged registry and not an inline entry | `rhei validate` / settings load | Hard error. Same class as a dangling `model:` or `agent:` reference. |
   714	| Registry entry exists but the MCP server cannot start, URL is unreachable, the handshake times out, or a skill path does not exist | Agent spawn | Depends on the entry's `optional` flag (see below). |
   715	| MCP server starts but crashes mid-session | During agent execution | The agent surfaces the protocol error; Rhei does not intervene. The failure appears in the agent log. |
   716	
   717	An MCP server or skill is considered **available** when:
   718	
   719	- For `command`-based MCP servers: the subprocess launched, the MCP handshake
   720	  completed, and the server remained alive, all within its `startup_timeout`
   721	  (default `10s`).
   722	- For `url`-based MCP servers: the transport-level connection completed and
   723	  the MCP handshake succeeded within `startup_timeout`.
   724	- For skills: the configured `path` exists and is readable.
   725	
   726	### Required vs optional entries
   727	
   728	Per-state `mcp_servers` and `skills` entries may be declared required (the
   729	default) or `optional: true`. The `defaults` lists in `settings.json` follow
   730	the same rules.
   731	
   732	- **Required (default):** if the entry fails its availability check,
   733	  `rhei run` does not spawn the agent. The engine looks for an
   734	  `mcp_unavailable` or `skill_unavailable` transition from the current state
   735	  in `states.yaml`:
   736	  - If one is declared, it fires with `triggeredBy: 'system'`. The callback
   737	    receives the unavailable ids in `transitionData.unavailable`.
   738	  - Otherwise the task stays in its current state and the engine logs
   739	    `error: required tooling unavailable for task {id} in state '{state}':
   740	    <id1>, <id2>`. `--continue-on-error` behaves the same way it does for
   741	    agent exits: the engine logs and skips the task.
   742	- **Optional (`optional: true`):** if the entry fails, `rhei run` logs a
   743	  warning and spawns the agent with the remaining resolved tooling. The
   744	  prompt's template variables and env vars reflect availability so
   745	  instructions and callbacks can branch. Missing optional skills are always
   746	  non-fatal and emit the same warning regardless of agent support.
   747	
   748	An unsupported agent (one whose profile declares no `mcp_flag` /
   749	`mcp_config_flag` for a required MCP entry, or no `skill_flag` for a required
   750	skill entry) is treated identically to an availability failure: required
   751	entries escalate to the `*_unavailable` path; optional entries produce a
   752	warning and are dropped.
   753	
   754	See [Transitions Specification](rhei-transitions.spec.md) for declaring
   755	`mcp_unavailable` / `skill_unavailable` transitions and
   756	[States Specification — Template Variables](rhei-states.spec.md#template-variables-in-instructions-and-personality)
   757	for `{mcp.<name>.available}` and `{skill.<id>.available}` in prompts.
   758	
   759	## Timeout Handling
   760	
   761	### Configuration
   762	
   763	Timeout can be set at four levels:
   764	
   765	1. **Per-state** — `agent_timeout` field on a state definition:
   766	   ```yaml
   767	   states:
   768	     pending:
   769	       agent_timeout: 30m
   770	   ```
   771	
   772	2. **Per-model/agent binding** — `timeout` field in a model profile's `agents` binding:
   773	   ```json
   774	   {
   775	     "models": {
   776	       "impl-fast": {
   777	         "provider": "anthropic",
   778	         "model": "claude-sonnet-4-6",
   779	         "agents": {
   780	           "claude-code": { "timeout": "45m" }
   781	         }
   782	       }
   783	     }
   784	   }
   785	   ```
   786	
   787	3. **Per-agent profile** — `timeout` field on an entry in the `agents`
   788	   registry:
   789	   ```json
   790	   {
   791	     "agents": {
   792	       "my-agent": { "command": ["my-agent"], "timeout": "1h" }
   793	     }
   794	   }
   795	   ```
   796	
   797	4. **Defaults** — `defaults.agent_timeout` in settings:
   798	   ```json
   799	   { "defaults": { "agent_timeout": "30m" } }
   800	   ```
   801	
   802	Resolution: state-level > model-agent binding > agent-profile > settings defaults.
   803	
   804	Under `orchestrator` [Completion Authority](#completion-authority), a timeout
   805	must resolve to a finite value at some level of the chain; missing timeouts on
   806	orchestrator-driven states are a validation error. Under `worker` authority
   807	the resolution is optional and the engine does not impose a timeout on manual
   808	work.
   809	
   810	### Duration Format
   811	
   812	Durations use a human-readable format: `30s`, `5m`, `1h`, `2h30m`. Supported units:
   813	
   814	| Unit | Suffix | Example |
   815	|------|--------|---------|
   816	| Seconds | `s` | `30s` |
   817	| Minutes | `m` | `5m` |
   818	| Hours | `h` | `1h` |
   819	
   820	Units can be combined: `1h30m`, `2h15m30s`.
   821	
   822	### Timeout Behavior
   823	
   824	When an agent process exceeds its timeout:
   825	
   826	1. `rhei run` sends `SIGTERM` to the agent process.
   827	2. After a 10-second grace period, if the process has not exited, send `SIGKILL`.
   828	3. Log to the task log: `agent timed out after {duration}`.
   829	4. Look for a timeout transition from the current state in the state machine.
   830	5. If a timeout transition exists, fire it (with its `on_leave`/`on_enter` callbacks).
   831	6. If no timeout transition exists, the task remains in its current state and the engine logs a warning.
   832	
   833	### Timeout Transitions
   834	
   835	Timeout transitions are declared in the `transitions` array with the `timeout` field. The existing `timeout` field in the transition schema (see [Transitions Specification](rhei-transitions.spec.md#transition-definition)) is used by `rhei run` to determine what to do when an agent times out.
   836	
   837	When a task is being worked by an agent and the agent exceeds the state's timeout:
   838	
   839	1. The engine kills the agent process.
   840	2. The engine evaluates timeout transitions from the current state.
   841	3. The first matching timeout transition fires.
   842	
   843	The `triggeredBy` field on these transitions is set to `'system'`.
   844	
   845	Example:
   846	
   847	```yaml
   848	states:
   849	  pending:
   850	    description: Task is ready for implementation.
   851	    model: impl-fast
   852	    agent_timeout: 30m
   853	
   854	  timed-out:
   855	    description: Agent failed to complete within the time budget.
   856	    gating: true
   857	    instructions: |
   858	      The agent timed out while working on this task. A human must decide:
   859	      - Return to `pending` for another attempt
   860	      - Cancel the task
   861	      - Increase the timeout and retry
   862	
   863	transitions:
   864	  - from: pending
   865	    to: timed-out
   866	    description: Agent exceeded the time budget
   867	    timeout: 30m
   868	    on_enter: "cli:bash ./workflow.sh notify-timeout"
   869	
   870	  - from: timed-out
   871	    to: pending
   872	    description: Human decided to retry
   873	
   874	  - from: timed-out
   875	    to: cancelled
   876	    description: Human decided to abandon after timeout
   877	```
   878	
   879	The `timeout` field on the transition and `agent_timeout` on the state serve different roles:
   880	
   881	| Field | Where | Purpose |
   882	|-------|-------|---------|
   883	| `agent_timeout` | State definition | How long the engine waits before killing the agent process |
   884	| `timeout` | Transition definition | Which transition fires when a timeout occurs (existing field, now also used by agent mode) |
   885	
   886	When `agent_timeout` is set on a state but no transition with `timeout` exists from that state, the agent is killed but the task remains in its current state with a warning logged.
   887	
   888	### Timeout Callbacks
   889	
   890	Timeout transitions support the same `on_leave` and `on_enter` callbacks as any other transition. This enables notification, logging, or cleanup on timeout:
   891	
   892	```yaml
   893	transitions:
   894	  - from: pending
   895	    to: timed-out
   896	    description: Agent exceeded time budget
   897	    timeout: 30m
   898	    on_leave: "cli:bash ./workflow.sh save-partial-work"
   899	    on_enter: "cli:bash ./workflow.sh notify-timeout"
   900	```
   901	
   902	The callback receives a `TransitionContext` with `triggeredBy: 'system'` and the timeout duration in `transitionData.timeout`.
   903	
   904	## Log Capture
   905	
   906	All agent stdout and stderr are captured to log files in the `runtime/logs/` directory relative to the workspace or plan root.
   907	
   908	### Log File Naming
   909	
   910	| Scenario | Log file path |
   911	|----------|---------------|
   912	| Simple state | `runtime/logs/task-{task_id}-{state}.log` |
   913	| Counted-loop state | `runtime/logs/task-{task_id}-{state}-{visit_count}.log` |
   914	| Model-specific state | `runtime/logs/task-{task_id}-{state}-{model}.log` |
   915	| Both visits and model | `runtime/logs/task-{task_id}-{state}-{model}-{visit_count}.log` |
   916	
   917	### Log Format
   918	
   919	Each log file contains:
   920	
   921	```
   922	=== rhei agent log v1 ===
   923	agent: claude-code
   924	model: impl-fast
   925	provider: anthropic
   926	model_name: claude-sonnet-4-6
   927	task: 3
   928	state: pending
   929	started: 2026-04-20T10:30:00Z
   930	timeout: 30m
   931	plan: /home/user/project/plan.rhei.md
   932	mcp_servers: postgres,grafana?
   933	skills: test-authoring
   934	===
   935	
   936	<raw agent stdout and stderr, interleaved>
   937	
   938	=== exit ===
   939	code: 0
   940	duration: 4m23s
   941	ended: 2026-04-20T10:34:23Z
   942	===
   943	```
   944	
   945	The header and footer are added by `rhei run`. The `v1` suffix is the log format version — increment it when the header/footer structure changes. The body is the raw, unmodified output of the agent process.
   946	
   947	Each entry in `mcp_servers:` and `skills:` is the resolved id; an entry
   948	suffixed with `?` was declared `optional: true` and failed its availability
   949	check — it was dropped before spawn and is recorded for diagnostics. A
   950	missing line means the state declared no entries of that kind.
   951	
   952	### Log Directory
   953	
   954	`runtime/logs/` is created automatically by `rhei run` if it does not exist. `rhei reset` removes the entire `runtime/` directory, including logs.
   955	
   956	## Dry-Run Output
   957	
   958	`rhei run --dry-run` in agent mode shows what would be spawned without executing:
   959	
   960	```
   961	Pass 1: 2 ready, 0 terminal, 5 total.
   962	
   963	Would spawn: claude -p "<prompt...>" --model claude-sonnet-4-6
   964	  Task 1: Set up database schema [draft -> pending]
   965	  Agent: claude-code, Model: impl-fast (anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6), Timeout: 30m
   966	  Log: runtime/logs/task-1-pending.log
   967	
   968	Would spawn: claude -p "<prompt...>" --model claude-sonnet-4-6
   969	  Task 3: Write frontend components [draft -> pending]
   970	  Agent: claude-code, Model: impl-fast (anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6), Timeout: 30m
   971	  Log: runtime/logs/task-3-pending.log
   972	
   973	Dry run complete - no agents were spawned.
   974	```
   975	
   976	## `rhei run --no-agent` — Callback-Only Mode
   977	
   978	When `--no-agent` is passed, `rhei run` reverts to pre-agent behavior: it advances tasks through the state machine using transition callbacks only, without spawning any agent processes. This is the existing behavior for backward compatibility.
   979	
