     1	# Rhei Program States Specification
     2	
     3	This document specifies **program states** — states that execute a deterministic program or command instead of spawning an AI coding agent. Program states are the algorithmic complement to agent states: where agents receive prompts and make decisions, programs execute a fixed command and let exit codes and file outputs determine workflow progression.
     4	
     5	For agent states see [Agents Specification](rhei-agents.spec.md). For the state machine format see [States Specification](rhei-states.spec.md).
     6	
     7	## Overview
     8	
     9	A program state runs a command as a subprocess. The command receives context through environment variables and command-line template variables. Its exit code and file outputs determine what happens next. This is the right choice for deterministic workflow steps — builds, tests, linting, deployment, data transforms, migrations — where an AI agent would add latency and cost without value.
    10	
    11	Program states participate in the same `rhei run` execution loop as agent states. They support the same artifact contracts, counted loops, timeout handling, log capture, and callback integration. The only difference is how the work is performed: a fixed command instead of a prompted agent.
    12	
    13	## Program Declaration
    14	
    15	### String Form
    16	
    17	The simplest form runs a shell command:
    18	
    19	```yaml
    20	states:
    21	  build:
    22	    description: Build the project
    23	    program: "npm run build"
    24	    program_timeout: 10m
    25	```
    26	
    27	String-form commands are executed via the system shell (`/bin/sh -c` on Unix, `cmd /c` on Windows).
    28	
    29	### Object Form
    30	
    31	For more control over execution:
    32	
    33	```yaml
    34	states:
    35	  build:
    36	    description: Build the project
    37	    program:
    38	      command: ["npm", "run", "build"]
    39	      env:
    40	        NODE_ENV: production
    41	      working_directory: ./packages/core
    42	    program_timeout: 10m
    43	```
    44	
    45	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
    46	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
    47	| `command` | string or string array | Yes | The command to execute. Array form bypasses the shell (exec directly). String form runs via shell. |
    48	| `env` | object | No | Additional environment variables merged with the base set. Values support template variables. |
    49	| `working_directory` | string | No | Override the subprocess working directory. Relative to workspace root. Supports template variables. Default: workspace root. |
    50	| `shell` | boolean | No | Force shell execution even for array-form commands. Default: `false` for arrays, `true` for strings. |
    51	
    52	### Template Variables in Commands
    53	
    54	Program commands support the same template variables as `instructions` and agent prompts:
    55	
    56	```yaml
    57	states:
    58	  test:
    59	    program: "./scripts/test.sh {task_id}"
    60	    program_timeout: 5m
    61	
    62	  deploy:
    63	    program:
    64	      command: ["./scripts/deploy.sh", "--env", "{meta.deploy_env}"]
    65	      env:
    66	        TASK_TITLE: "{task_title}"
    67	```
    68	
    69	Variables are resolved by `rhei run` before spawning the process, using the same resolution rules as agent prompt composition. See [Template Variables](rhei-states.spec.md#template-variables-in-instructions-and-personality).
    70	
    71	## Environment Variables
    72	
    73	Program subprocesses inherit the same base environment as agent subprocesses:
    74	
    75	| Variable | Value |
    76	|----------|-------|
    77	| `RHEI_PLAN_PATH` | Absolute path to the plan file or workspace directory |
    78	| `RHEI_TASK_ID` | Current task identifier |
    79	| `RHEI_STATE` | Current state name |
    80	| `RHEI_VISIT_COUNT` | Current visit number (for counted-loop states) |
    81	| `RHEI_INPUT_<NAME>_EXISTS` | `true` or `false` — whether the declared input artifact exists on disk. Set for every declared input, required or optional. `<NAME>` is the artifact `name` uppercased with hyphens and spaces replaced by underscores (e.g., `continuation-notes` → `RHEI_INPUT_CONTINUATION_NOTES_EXISTS`). |
    82	| `RHEI_INPUT_<NAME>_PATH` | Resolved path of the declared input artifact. Set for every declared input regardless of whether the file exists. Same name transform as `RHEI_INPUT_<NAME>_EXISTS`. |
    83	
    84	Additional variables declared in `program.env` are merged on top of this base set. When a `program.env` key collides with a base variable, the `program.env` value wins.
    85	
    86	The working directory defaults to the workspace root (for directory workspaces) or the plan file's parent directory (for single-file plans), unless overridden by `program.working_directory`.
    87	
    88	## Exit-Code Transitions
    89	
    90	Programs communicate their outcome through exit codes. Transitions from program states can declare an `exit_code` condition that matches specific exit values, enabling automatic routing without the program needing to call `rhei transition` directly.
    91	
    92	```yaml
    93	states:
    94	  build:
    95	    description: Build the project
    96	    program: "make build"
    97	
    98	  test:
    99	    description: Run the test suite
   100	    program: "make test"
   101	
   102	  build-failed:
   103	    description: Build failed
   104	    gating: true
   105	
   106	  test-failed:
   107	    description: Tests failed
   108	    gating: true
   109	
   110	transitions:
   111	  - from: build
   112	    to: test
   113	    description: Build succeeded
   114	    exit_code: 0
   115	
   116	  - from: build
   117	    to: build-failed
   118	    description: Build failed
   119	    exit_code: nonzero
   120	
   121	  - from: test
   122	    to: completed
   123	    description: All tests passed
   124	    exit_code: 0
   125	
   126	  - from: test
   127	    to: test-failed
   128	    description: Tests failed with assertion errors
   129	    exit_code: [1, 2]
   130	
   131	  - from: test
   132	    to: test-failed
   133	    description: Test infrastructure error
   134	    exit_code: nonzero
   135	```
   136	
   137	### `exit_code` Field
   138	
   139	Added to the transition definition schema (see [Transitions Specification](rhei-transitions.spec.md)):
   140	
   141	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   142	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   143	| `exit_code` | integer, integer array, or `"nonzero"` | No | Exit-code condition for automatic transitions from program states. |
   144	
   145	Values:
   146	- **integer** (`0`, `1`, `42`): matches that exact exit code.
   147	- **integer array** (`[1, 2, 3]`): matches any listed exit code.
   148	- **`"nonzero"`**: matches any non-zero exit code not already matched by a more specific transition from the same source state.
   149	
   150	### Evaluation Order
   151	
   152	When a program exits and has not already advanced the task (via `rhei transition` or `rhei complete`):
   153	
   154	1. Collect all transitions from the current state that declare an `exit_code` field.
   155	2. Evaluate specific matches first: integer and integer-array conditions are checked against the actual exit code.
   156	3. If no specific match and the exit code is non-zero, evaluate `"nonzero"` transitions.
   157	4. If exactly one transition matches, fire it (with its `on_leave`/`on_enter` callbacks).
   158	5. If multiple transitions match at the same specificity level, also evaluate `condition` fields to disambiguate. If still ambiguous after conditions, it is a validation error.
   159	6. If no transition matches and exit code is `0`, log a warning: `warning: program exited 0 but task {id} did not advance from '{state}'`.
   160	7. If no transition matches and exit code is non-zero, log an error and apply the `--continue-on-error` policy.
   161	
   162	### Mixing Exit-Code and Manual Transitions
   163	
   164	Programs may also call `rhei transition` or `rhei complete` directly via subprocess invocation, just like agents. When a program does so, the task state changes before the program exits, and exit-code evaluation is skipped entirely — the explicit transition takes precedence.
   165	
   166	If a transition from a program state has no `exit_code` field, it is available for manual invocation (`rhei transition`) or for the program to call directly, but it will never be selected by exit-code evaluation.
   167	
   168	This allows hybrid approaches where a program handles the common case via exit codes and calls `rhei transition` for edge cases that need more nuanced routing.
   169	
   170	## Timeout Handling
   171	
   172	Program timeout uses the same mechanism as agent timeout.
   173	
   174	### Configuration
   175	
   176	Timeout can be set at three levels:
   177	
   178	1. **Per-state** — `program_timeout` field on the state definition:
   179	   ```yaml
   180	   states:
   181	     build:
   182	       program: "make build"
   183	       program_timeout: 10m
   184	   ```
   185	
   186	2. **Global default** — `program_timeout` in settings:
   187	   ```json
   188	   { "program_timeout": "15m" }
   189	   ```
   190	
   191	3. **CLI override** — `--program-timeout` flag on `rhei run` overrides all levels.
   192	
   193	Resolution: CLI override > state-level > settings-level.
   194	
   195	Duration format is the same as `agent_timeout`: `30s`, `5m`, `1h`, `2h30m`. See [Agents Specification — Duration Format](rhei-agents.spec.md#duration-format).
   196	
   197	### Behavior
   198	
   199	Program timeout uses the same SIGTERM → 10 s grace → SIGKILL sequence and the same timeout-transition evaluation as agent timeout. See [Agents Specification — Timeout Behavior](rhei-agents.spec.md#timeout-behavior) for the full step-by-step. The only program-specific differences are:
   200	
   201	- The log line reads `program timed out after {duration}` (not `agent timed out`).
   202	- The state-level field is `program_timeout` (not `agent_timeout`).
   203	
   204	Timeout transitions fire with `triggeredBy: 'system'`. See [Transitions Specification — Agent Timeout Trigger](rhei-transitions.spec.md#6-agent-timeout-trigger-triggeredby-system) for the transition selection rules.
   205	
   206	## Log Capture
   207	
   208	Program stdout and stderr are captured using the same log format and naming conventions as agents. All output is written to `runtime/logs/` relative to the workspace or plan root.
   209	
   210	### Log File Naming
   211	
   212	| Scenario | Log file path |
   213	|----------|---------------|
   214	| Simple state | `runtime/logs/task-{task_id}-{state}.log` |
   215	| Counted-loop state | `runtime/logs/task-{task_id}-{state}-{visit_count}.log` |
   216	
   217	### Log Format
   218	
   219	Programs use the same header / body / footer structure as agent logs (see [Agents Specification — Log Format](rhei-agents.spec.md#log-format)). The program-specific differences are:
   220	
   221	- The header marker is `=== rhei program log v1 ===` (not `rhei agent log v1`).
   222	- The header carries `program:` (the resolved command) instead of `agent:`, `model:`, `provider:`, `model_name:`, `mcp_servers:`, and `skills:` — those fields are agent-only.
   223	- Everything else (body, `=== exit ===` footer with `code` / `duration` / `ended`) is identical.
   224	
   225	Example:
   226	
   227	```
   228	=== rhei program log v1 ===
   229	program: npm run build
   230	task: 3
   231	state: build
   232	started: 2026-04-20T10:30:00Z
   233	timeout: 10m
   234	plan: /home/user/project/plan.rhei.md
   235	===
   236	
   237	<raw program stdout and stderr, interleaved>
   238	
   239	=== exit ===
   240	code: 0
   241	duration: 2m15s
   242	ended: 2026-04-20T10:32:15Z
   243	===
   244	```
   245	
   246	## `rhei run` Integration
   247	
   248	### Execution Loop
   249	
   250	Program states integrate into the same `rhei run` loop as agent states. The resolution priority when `rhei run` encounters a state is:
   251	
   252	1. State declares `program` → spawn program.
   253	2. State declares `agent` → spawn agent.
   254	3. Project/global agent settings → spawn agent.
   255	4. No program or agent configured → fail with error.
   256	
   257	Programs take precedence because they are declared explicitly on the state and represent a deliberate choice for deterministic execution.
   258	
   259	### Sequential Mode
   260	
   261	Within the sequential execution loop (see [Agents Specification](rhei-agents.spec.md#sequential-mode-default---parallel-1)):
   262	
   263	1. Find the next claimable task.
   264	2. Check the task's current state.
   265	3. If the state declares `program`, resolve and expand the command.
   266	4. Log the spawn to `runtime/logs/task-{task_id}-{state}[-{visit_count}].log`.
   267	5. Spawn the program as a subprocess.
   268	6. Wait for exit (subject to `program_timeout`).
   269	7. Re-read the plan from disk. Check whether the task's state changed — `rhei transition` and `rhei complete` are file-mutating operations that write the new state directly to the plan file.
   270	8. If state changed, log the transition and continue the loop.
   271	9. If state did not change, evaluate exit-code transitions.
   272	10. If an exit-code transition matches, fire it and continue.
   273	11. If no match: warning (exit 0) or error (exit non-zero).
   274	
   275	### Parallel Mode
   276	
   277	Programs respect the same independence rules as agents in parallel mode. Independent tasks with program states can run concurrently up to `--parallel N`.
   278	
   279	### Flags
   280	
   281	| Flag | Effect on Program States |
   282	|------|--------------------------|
   283	| `--dry-run` | Shows the command that would be spawned, without executing |
   284	| `--no-agent` | No effect on program states (programs are not agents) |
   285	| `--no-program` | Suppresses program spawning; fall back to callback-only advancement |
   286	| `--parallel <N>` | Programs respect the same independence and concurrency rules as agents |
   287	| `--program-timeout <duration>` | Override program timeout for this run |
   288	
   289	### Dry-Run Output
   290	
   291	```
   292	Pass 1: 2 ready, 0 terminal, 5 total.
   293	
   294	Would run: npm run build
   295	  Task 1: Build the project [draft -> build]
   296	  Timeout: 10m
   297	  Log: runtime/logs/task-1-build.log
   298	
   299	Would spawn: claude -p "<prompt...>" --model claude-sonnet-4-6
   300	  Task 3: Write documentation [draft -> pending]
   301	  Agent: claude-code, Model: impl-fast (anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6), Timeout: 30m
   302	  Log: runtime/logs/task-3-pending.log
   303	
   304	Dry run complete - nothing was executed.
   305	```
   306	
   307	### Gating States
   308	
   309	A state must not declare both `program` and `gating: true`. Programs execute autonomously; gating states require human action. This combination is a validation error.
   310	
   311	## Interaction with Other Features
   312	
   313	### Artifact Contracts
   314	
   315	Program states use the same `inputs` / `outputs` artifact contracts as any other state — see [States Specification — Artifact Contracts](rhei-states.spec.md#artifact-contracts) for the schema, path template variables, and general semantics.
   316	
   317	Program-specific timing:
   318	
   319	- Required `inputs` are checked before the program is spawned. Missing required inputs abort the spawn.
   320	- Required `outputs` are checked after the program exits and before the exit-code transition is committed. A zero exit with a missing required output leaves the task in its current state.
   321	
   322	```yaml
   323	states:
   324	  build:
   325	    program: "make build"
   326	    program_timeout: 10m
   327	    outputs:
   328	      - name: bundle
   329	        path: dist/bundle.js
   330	
   331	  test:
   332	    program: "make test"
   333	    program_timeout: 15m
   334	    inputs:
   335	      - name: bundle
   336	        path: dist/bundle.js
   337	    outputs:
   338	      - name: coverage
   339	        path: coverage/lcov.info
   340	```
   341	
   342	### Callbacks
   343	
   344	Programs and callbacks are complementary, the same as agents and callbacks:
   345	
   346	1. The program runs and exits.
   347	2. Exit-code transition evaluation determines the target state.
   348	3. The selected transition's `on_leave` and `on_enter` callbacks execute as usual.
   349	
   350	```yaml
   351	transitions:
   352	  - from: build
   353	    to: test
   354	    exit_code: 0
   355	    on_leave: "cli:bash ./workflow.sh archive-build"
   356	    on_enter: "cli:bash ./workflow.sh prepare-test-env"
   357	```
   358	
   359	### Counted Loops
   360	
   361	Programs work with `visits` for retry and iteration patterns:
   362	
   363	```yaml
   364	states:
   365	  deploy:
   366	    description: Deploy to staging
   367	    program: "./scripts/deploy.sh staging"
   368	    program_timeout: 15m
   369	    visits: 3
   370	
   371	  deploy-failed:
   372	    description: Deployment exhausted retries
   373	    gating: true
   374	
   375	  verify:
   376	    description: Verify the deployment
   377	    program: "./scripts/verify.sh staging"
   378	    program_timeout: 5m
   379	
   380	transitions:
   381	  - from: deploy
   382	    to: deploy
   383	    description: Retry deployment
   384	    exit_code: nonzero
   385	    condition: visitCount < visits
   386	
   387	  - from: deploy
   388	    to: deploy-failed
   389	    description: Deployment exhausted retries
   390	    exit_code: nonzero
   391	    condition: visitCount >= visits
   392	
   393	  - from: deploy
   394	    to: verify
   395	    description: Deployment succeeded
   396	    exit_code: 0
   397	```
   398	
   399	### Instructions and Personality
   400	
   401	`instructions` on program states serve as documentation — they describe what the program does for human operators viewing `rhei next` output. They are not passed to the program.
   402	
   403	`personality` is ignored for program states.
   404	
   405	### Models
   406	
   407	`model` and `all_models` are ignored for program states. Programs do not use AI models. Declaring both `program` and `model`/`all_models` on the same state is a validation warning (not an error, to allow gradual migration).
   408	
   409	## Validation Rules
   410	
   411	### State-Level
   412	
   413	- `state.program`, when present, must be a non-empty string or a valid program object with at least a `command` field.
   414	- A state must not declare both `agent` and `program`.
   415	- `state.program` on a `final: true` state is a validation error (terminal states have no work to execute).
   416	- `state.program` on a `gating: true` state is a validation error (gating states require human action).
   417	- `state.program_timeout`, when present, must be a valid duration string (e.g., `30s`, `5m`, `1h`, `2h30m`).
   418	- `program.command`, when present as an array, must be a non-empty array of strings.
   419	- `program.env` values must be strings (after template variable resolution).
   420	- `program.working_directory`, when present, must resolve to a path within the workspace root after template expansion.
   421	
   422	### Transition-Level
   423	
   424	- Transitions with `exit_code` must originate from a state that declares `program`. An `exit_code` on a transition from a non-program state is a validation error.
   425	- Exit-code transitions from the same source state must not have overlapping values at the same specificity. Specifically:
   426	  - Two specific integers must not be equal.
   427	  - Two integer arrays must not share any value.
   428	  - A specific integer must not appear in another transition's integer array.
   429	  - At most one `"nonzero"` transition per source state (before `condition` disambiguation).
   430	- When multiple `"nonzero"` or overlapping transitions exist from the same source, they must have mutually exclusive `condition` fields to disambiguate.
   431	
   432	## Per-State Fields (additions to States Specification)
   433	
   434	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   435	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   436	| `program` | string or object | No | The program command to execute in this state. Mutually exclusive with `agent`. String form runs via shell. Object form specifies `command`, `env`, `working_directory`, and `shell`. |
   437	| `program_timeout` | string | No | Maximum time the program may run before being killed (e.g., `10m`, `1h`). Same duration format and timeout handling as `agent_timeout`. |
   438	
   439	## Transition Field (addition to Transitions Specification)
   440	
   441	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   442	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   443	| `exit_code` | integer, integer array, or `"nonzero"` | No | Exit-code condition for transitions from program states. Only evaluated when the program exits without calling `rhei transition`. |
   444	
   445	## Example: CI Pipeline — Pure Program Workflow
   446	
   447	A fully deterministic pipeline with no AI agents:
   448	
   449	```yaml
   450	name: ci-pipeline
   451	version: 1.0
   452	
   453	states:
   454	  lint:
   455	    description: Run linters and formatters

 succeeded in 313ms:
     1	# Transition Callback Examples
